Central question in text mining

A central question in text mining and natural language processing is how to quantify what a document is about.

There is a measure or score called tf-idf which is a measure or score of a wordâs importance to a document/body of work when examining in the context of a collection/corpus. Let us break down this concept.

One measure of how important a word to a specific body of work (e.g., Jane Austenâs Sense & Sensibility), may be is its term frequency (tf) to represent how frequently a word occurs.

For a body of work (e.g., book, chapter), the term frequency (tf) is formally defined as:

\[ \frac{n_{word_{specific}}}{n_{word_{all}}} \]

where \(n_{word_{specific}}\) = the number of a word of interest in the body of work (e.g., the number of âprejudiceâ mentions in âSense & Sensibilityâ) and \(n_{word_{all}}\) = total words in the body of work (e.g.Â âSense & Sensibilityâ).

There are words in a document, however, that occur many times but may not be important; in English, these are probably words like âtheâ, âisâ, âofâ, and so forth. We defined these as stop words. We manually removed words that are considered stop words. There is always subjectivity in choosing stop words though.

Another approach when you are comparing a body of work (e.g., book by book from Jane Austenâs work) is to look at a termâs inverse document frequency (idf), which decreases the weight for commonly used words and increases the weight for words that are not used very much in a collection of documents.

Real word meaning or implication: We must use some mathematical or statistical way to penalize common words across a body of work. For example, âtheâ is a word that exists across the six novels, so tf (term frequency) has to be penalized.

This can be combined with term frequency to calculate a termâs tf-idf (the two quantities multiplied together), the frequency of a term adjusted for how rarely it is used.

The statistic tf-idf is intended to measure how important a word is to a document in a collection (or corpus) of documents(e.g., importance of a specific word in one novel when we are looking across a collection of novels or to one website in a collection of websites).

Let us formally defined the idf equation as:

\[ idf(term) = ln(\frac{n_{documents}}{n_{Documents Containing Term}}) \]

Examples for the Jane Austen Books: \(idf('the') = ln(\frac{6}{6}) = ln(1) = 0\) because there are 6 Jane Austen books within our analysis, and the word âtheâ appears in all 6.

Meanwhile for cry:

\(idf('cry') = ln(\frac{6}{5}) = 0.1823216\)

because there are 6 Jane Austen books within our analysis, and the word âcryâ appears in 5.

Again: tf-idf is two quantities multiplied together. So regardless of the tf value for the word âtheâ, the tf-idf (again multiplication) is zero because âtheâ appeared in all six of Jane Austenâs book.

So you may think of tf-idf as a score to determine the importance of words in a body of work since the score is penalized more heavily the more it exist in other body of work.

n-grams and word-pairings

So far weâve considered words as individual units, and considered their relationships to sentiments or to documents.

However, many interesting text analyses are based on the relationships between words, whether examining which words tend to follow others immediately, or that tend to co-occur within the same documents.

In this lecture/lab section, weâll explore some of the methods tidytext offers for calculating and visualizing relationships between words in your text dataset.

This includes the token = "ngrams" argument in unnest_tokens(), which tokenizes by pairs of adjacent words rather than by individual ones.

Bigrams: Word Pairings

When n = 2 for ngrams, we are looking into word pairings (also known as bigrams).

This data structure below is still a variation of the tidy text format. It is structured as one-token-per-row but each token now represents a bigram.

austen_pair_tidy <- austen_books() |>
  unnest_tokens(output = bigram, input = text, token = "ngrams", n = 2) |>
  filter(!is.na(bigram)) # this removes rows with empty bigram fields

As one might expect, a lot of the most common bigrams are pairs of common (uninteresting) words, such as of the and to be: what we call âstop-wordsâ.

This is a useful time to use tidyrâs separate(), which splits a column into multiple based on a delimiter (a character or set of characters that is guaranteed to split/chop a body of text).

This lets us separate it into two columns, âword1â and âword2â, at which point we can remove cases where either word is a stop-word. tidyr is part of the tidyverse package, so this is loaded via library(tidyverse).

bigram_separated <- austen_pair_tidy |>
  separate(col = bigram, 
           into = c("word1", "word2"),
           sep = " ")
# col: is the column/variable to separate
# into: lets R know that you want the new columns to be named word1, word2
# sep = " ": lets R know that bigram words is seperated by white space,
# it will use this white space to cut bigram into word1 and word2

head(bigram_separated, 10)

# loads stop_words into your R env't
data("stop_words")

# if the bigram pair has a stop word, it gets removed
bigrams_filtered <- bigram_separated |>
  filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word) |>
  filter(!word2 %in% stop_words$word)

Trigrams: Three-Word Pairings (n=3)

Similar to n=2 (bigrams) with some minor tweaks (e.g., n = 3, addition of âword3â, etc).

Part of the reason why I have this code is to show you a consolidated code of combining what we did for bigram but in one code that uses pipes.

This is the way the book codes but if you dislike this code that does too much, follow broken down code structure for you did for bigram above.

I generally donât recommend you code this way (the way your book and the code below codes) if youâre a beginner programmer. Otherwise, you are more than welcome to follow this structure:

ngram and tf-idf

tf-idf again is a measure of importance of a word to a document/body of work in a collection/corpus.

Let us again create a tidy data frame of the Jane Austen novels with bigrams:

austen_pair_tidy <- austen_books() |>
  unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2) |>
  filter(!is.na(bigram)) # this removes rows with empty bigram fields

austen_bigram_tf_idf <- austen_pair_tidy |>
  group_by(book, bigram) |>
  summarise(n = n()) |>
  bind_tf_idf(term = bigram, document = book, n = n) |>
  group_by(book) |>
  slice_max(tf_idf, n = 10)

Suppose we want to plot what is called a graph or network plot that shows connectivity of words. Due to limited space, we need to be selective for word pairs that appear a lot only (cut off is subjective and you may need to play around with the cut off) to highlight word pairs that are prominent.

Let us create a data subset of bigrams_filtered in igraphâs network format where n > 20 called bigrams_graph:

bigrams_graph <- bigrams_filtered |> 
  filter(n > 20) |>
  graph_from_data_frame() 
# graph_from_data_frame() transfers from data frame into igraph's network format
# IMPORTANT: make sure word1 and word2 are always the first two columns of the data frame or table before using graph_from_data_frame()

# shows you some basic information about the igraph data

Now that we have bigrams_graph which is a igraph-formatted data after using igraphâs graph_from_data_frame(), we should use the following code that uses ggraphâs ggraph():

# this code makes sure the graph is reproducible since ggraph applies 'randomness' in the creation of graph (i.e., not including set.seed() leads to ggraph creating unique graphs every single time you run the code)
# place any integer inside and if you don't like the graph, change it
set.seed(1) 

ggraph(bigrams_graph, layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_link() +
  geom_node_point() +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), vjust = 1, hjust = 1)
# added during class to set cut off to a different number
bigrams_graph <- bigrams_filtered |> 
  filter(n > 40) |>
  graph_from_data_frame() 

set.seed(1) 

# by changing from n > 25 to n > 40, we created a less busy/compacted graph that is easier to read
ggraph(bigrams_graph, layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_link() +
  geom_node_point() +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), vjust = 1, hjust = 1)

Some sample customization you can implement to made the bare-bones graph or network plot look nicer (again, if you donât like the current arrange of your plot, change the number within set.seed(). When you have time, play around some of the numbers in the customization provided to see their impact!

set.seed(12313)

ggraph(bigrams_graph, layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_link(aes(edge_alpha = n), 
                 show.legend = FALSE, 
                 end_cap = circle(.07, 'inches'), 
                 arrow = grid::arrow(type = "closed", 
                                      length = unit(.15, "inches"))) +
  geom_node_point(color = "lightblue", size = 5) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), vjust = 1, hjust = 1)
